re thing. Digital is my expertise, bicoastal is my beat, and I bring the best of both to everyone I work with.</p>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\" el_class=\"phil-image\"][vc_single_image image=\"112\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"500x500\"][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Philosophy + Approach','','inherit','open','open','','10-revision-v1','','','2015-03-18 19:13:48','2015-03-18 19:13:48','',10,'http://abbot-water.com/10-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(253,1,'2015-03-18 19:22:31','2015-03-18 19:22:31','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_empty_space height=\"15px\"][/vc_column][vc_column][vc_row_inner el_class=\"services-heading\"][vc_column_inner width=\"1/1\" el_class=\"services-march-heading\"][vc_column_text el_class=\"services-march-tagline\"]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Abbot + Water sits at the intersection of tech, strategy, media and marketing, from NYC to LA and everywhere in between.</p>\r\nWe work with a broad clientele of brands, publishers, ad tech companies and start-ups as digital marketing experts with a focus on content, video and media.\r\n\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class=\"services-sections\" gmbt_prlx_bg_type=\"parallax\" gmbt_prlx_break_parents=\"0\" gmbt_prlx_smooth_scrolling=\"\" gmbt_prlx_video_youtube_mute=\"\" gmbt_prlx_video_youtube_loop_trigger=\"0\" gmbt_prlx_video_aspect_ratio=\"16:9\" gmbt_prlx_parallax=\"none\" gmbt_prlx_speed=\"0.3\" gmbt_prlx_enable_mobile=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/1\" el_class=\"services-blurb\"][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/3\"][themestudio_title title=\"Brands\" align=\"align-center\" text_align=\"center\" title_color=\"#252525\" underline_color=\"#252525\"][/themestudio_title][vc_column_text]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Consider us your Digital SWAT team. We’ll marry your marketing and digital plans with informed, innovative and results-driven digital strategies, coordinating offline and online content, social marketing, technology, media, and communications across paid, owned and earned channels.</p>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/3\"][themestudio_title title=\"Start-Ups\" align=\"align-center\" text_align=\"center\" title_color=\"#252525\" underline_color=\"#252525\"][/themestudio_title][vc_column_text]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Creative and scrappy – our specialty when developing brand strategy and marketing for start-ups. If you have a product, and funding, it’s time to build your brand. We’ll create branding, content and media strategies that complement DR activities, to build targeted awareness and drive revenue.</p>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/3\"][themestudio_title title=\"Publishers / Ad Tech\" align=\"align-center\" text_align=\"center\" title_color=\"#252525\" underline_color=\"#252525\"][/themestudio_title][vc_column_text]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Brand-side marketing insight can help you differentiate yourself when fighting for ad dollars. Together we’ll focus on business development efforts to enrich your brand and agency relationships, develop new ad offerings and unlock video, content and native, all with monetization in mind.</p>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class=\"space-holder\" gmbt_prlx_bg_type=\"parallax\" gmbt_prlx_break_parents=\"0\" gmbt_prlx_smooth_scrolling=\"\" gmbt_prlx_video_youtube_mute=\"\" gmbt_prlx_video_youtube_loop_trigger=\"0\" gmbt_prlx_video_aspect_ratio=\"16:9\" gmbt_prlx_parallax=\"none\" gmbt_prlx_speed=\"0.3\" gmbt_prlx_enable_mobile=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_empty_space height=\"25px\" el_class=\"services-space\"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_text_separator title=\"SERVICES\" title_align=\"separator_align_center\" align=\"align_center\" color=\"grey\"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][themestudio_service_shortcode posts_per_page=\"8\" has_boder=\"yes\"][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Services','','inherit','open','open','','12-revision-v1','','','2015-03-18 19:22:31','2015-03-18 19:22:31','',12,'http://abbot-water.com/12-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(254,1,'2015-03-18 19:54:33','2015-03-18 19:54:33','Hello from Austin and another SXSW! Every year, the Interactive part of the festival grows bigger, and this year was no exception. If you\'ve never been, know this: it’s not a place for the faint of heart. This is a day-to-night affair, non-stop, for four days. It\'s panels, parties and pop-ups throughout the city, and it’s a great way to meet and connect with people you would never have met otherwise.\r\n<!--more-->\r\nBy request, I put together a roundup of what I think are the best of the best, by day, with commentary (below). Check out the content and the companies - it\'s worth your time. And if you do nothing else, do these three things: 1. Follow <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tnpuig\">Tomas Puig on Twitter</a>, who\'s workshop with Paul Dery was the single best thing I attended; 2. Buy Rick Webb\'s <a href=\"http://rickwebb.tumblr.com/\"><em>Agency: The Book</em></a><em>, </em>which sold out at SXSW; 3. Check out <a href=\"https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/881308232/only-on-kickstarter-the-leaders-guide-by-eric-ries\">Eric Ries\' crowd-sourced new book</a>, available only on Kickstarter and announced yesterday at SXSW.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 1</strong></p>\r\n<strong>Panel: <em>How to Remain Relevant in Today’s Digital Age, </em>Charles Barkley and Richard Deistch</strong> The conversation didn’t follow the panel title, but it was entertaining and filled with Barkley’s one-liners and a firm explanation of why he’s not on social media: it’s become a mean-spirited place. My favorite? His take on analytics: <em>Analytics is just stats. They just charge you more when they call it analytics. But it’s just stats.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Popup: How to Be a Change Agent, Brand Innovators </strong>An oasis in the SXSW storm, Brand Innovators hosted a full day of terrific programming and presentations featuring marketers, tech, and start-ups. If you are a brand marketer and don\'t attend their events, you should. <a href=\"http://brand-innovators.com/events/\">Find their calendar here.</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Party: NYT Magazine Relaunch Party</strong> Nothing much about the Times or the Magazine, but it did feature a great band, <a href=\"http://www.thesuffers.com/\"><em>The Suffers</em></a><em>, </em>at a classic venue – Mohawk on Red River.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 2</strong></p>\r\n<strong>Workshop: <em>Adv. Brand Marketing for Early Stage Companies, </em>Paul Dury and Tomas Puig</strong> The single best thing at SXSW. Marketing dollars + activities at early-stage companies need a different approach, and this four-hour workshop featured great content, in a digestible presentation and discussion, led by two experts. From how VC\'s judge a start-up via LTV and CAC to the basics of identifying your target market and USP, and addressing org structure of the modern marketing department, the material here was spot-on. And, contrast of Tomas and Paul\'s backgrounds brought the material to life in a relevant way. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tnpuig\">Tweet them for slides</a>!\r\n\r\n<strong>Day 2 Party: Rick Webb at the Yieldbot House </strong>Thanks to Yieldbot and Rick Webb for BBQ, Music, and FUN. The party celebrated <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Agency-Starting-Creative-Marketing-Advertising/dp/1137279869\">Rick\'s new book</a>, which is terrific. You can also catch my favorite post of his on Medium <a href=\"https://medium.com/galleys/f-king-timesheets-b3bb9d64beb8\">here</a>.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 3</strong></p>\r\n<strong>Day 3 Panel: <em>Future 15s Humans Not Consumers: Unconscious Emotions and Actions</em>, Douglas Van Praet </strong>A fascinating discussion about how we make choices - consciously and unconsciously - driven by emotion. The \"I like it and I don\'t know why\" effect is powerful, and Van Praet makes a good case for marketers to consider \'pattern interruption\' in creative execution. Check out his book <a href=\"http://unconsciousbranding.com/\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Day 3 Party: Dropbox </strong>With lots of competing parties, where to go/ Dropbox at <a href=\"http://shop.mellowjohnnys.com/?gclid=CIiAle7Wr8QCFQ8waQodon4ALw\">Mellow Johnny\'s Bike Shop</a>, of course! Great party, and a great 90\'s cover band, Angry Flannel (which founder Drew Houston is a member of). Nirvana, Jane\'s Addiction, represented!\r\n\r\n<strong>Roundup - Day 4</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Panel: <em>Everything Eric Ries Has Learned Since 2011</em>, Eric Ries, Ted Greenwald</strong> Fans of <a href=\"http://theleanstartup.com/\">The Lean Startup</a> author, rejoice! Eric Ries announced a new book, crowd-sourced on Kickstarter, called <a href=\"http://www.fastcompany.com/3043745/most-creative-people/the-lean-startup-author-eric-ries-is-crowdsourcing-his-next-book-via-ki\">The Leader\'s Guide</a>. Don\'t be intimidated - just be entertained - by the number of special \'packages\' you can choose from - it\'s part of the gimmick! For reference, I went with the All-Access Package.\r\n\r\nQuick shout out to my new friends at Tech.co, Chute, Partnered, and General Assembly - great meeting you guys. Rock on, Austin, and see you in 2016!','SXSW 2015 Roundup','','publish','open','open','','sxsw-2015-roundup','','','2015-03-31 15:17:33','2015-03-31 15:17:33','',0,'http://abbot-water.com/?p=254',0,'post','',0),
	(255,1,'2015-03-18 19:54:33','2015-03-18 19:54:33','<p>Hello from Austin and another SXSW!</p>\r\n<p>Every year, the Interactive part of the festival grows bigger, and this year was no exception. If you\'ve never been, know this: it’s not a place for the faint of heart. This is a day-to-night affair, non-stop, for four days. It\'s panels, parties and pop-ups throughout the city, and it’s a great way to meet and connect with people you would never have met otherwise.</p>\r\n<p>By request, I put together a roundup of what I think are the best of the best, by day, with commentary (below). Check out the content and the companies - it\'s worth your time. And if you do nothing else, do these three things: 1. Follow <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tnpuig\">Tomas Puig on Twitter</a>, who\'s workshop with Paul Dery was the single best thing I attended; 2. Buy Rick Webb\'s <a href=\"http://rickwebb.tumblr.com/\"><em>Agency: The Book</em></a><em>, </em>which sold out at SXSW; 3. Check out <a href=\"https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/881308232/only-on-kickstarter-the-leaders-guide-by-eric-ries\">Eric Ries\' crowd-sourced new book</a>, available only on Kickstarter and announced yesterday at SXSW.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 1</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Panel: <em>How to Remain Relevant in Today’s Digital Age, </em>Charles Barkley and Richard Deistch</strong> The conversation didn’t follow the panel title, but it was entertaining and filled with Barkley’s one-liners and a firm explanation of why he’s not on social media: it’s become a mean-spirited place. My favorite? His take on analytics: <em>Analytics is just stats. They just charge you more when they call it analytics. But it’s just stats.</em><p>\r\n<p><strong>Popup: How to Be a Change Agent, Brand Innovators </strong>An oasis in the SXSW storm, Brand Innovators hosted a full day of terrific programming and presentations featuring marketers, tech, and start-ups. If you are a brand marketer and don\'t attend their events, you should. <a href=\"http://brand-innovators.com/events/\">Find their calendar here.</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Party: NYT Magazine Relaunch Party</strong> Nothing much about the Times or the Magazine, but it did feature a great band, <a href=\"http://www.thesuffers.com/\"><em>The Suffers</em></a><em>, </em>at a classic venue – Mohawk on Red River.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 2</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Workshop: <em>Adv. Brand Marketing for Early Stage Companies, </em>Paul Dury and Tomas Puig</strong> The single best thing at SXSW. Marketing dollars + activities at early-stage companies need a different approach, and this four-hour workshop featured great content, in a digestible presentation and discussion, led by two experts. From how VC\'s judge a start-up via LTV and CAC to the basics of identifying your target market and USP, and addressing org structure of the modern marketing department, the material here was spot-on. And, contrast of Tomas and Paul\'s backgrounds brought the material to life in a relevant way. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tnpuig\">Tweet them for slides</a>!</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 2 Party: Rick Webb at the Yieldbot House </strong>Thanks to Yieldbot and Rick Webb for BBQ, Music, and FUN. The party celebrated <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Agency-Starting-Creative-Marketing-Advertising/dp/1137279869\">Rick\'s new book</a>, which is terrific. You can also catch my favorite post of his on Medium <a href=\"https://medium.com/galleys/f-king-timesheets-b3bb9d64beb8\">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 3</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 3 Panel: <em>Future 15s Humans Not Consumers: Unconscious Emotions and Actions</em>, Douglas Van Praet </strong>A fascinating discussion about how we make choices - consciously and unconsciously - driven by emotion. The \"I like it and I don\'t know why\" effect is powerful, and Van Praet makes a good case for marketers to consider \'pattern interruption\' in creative execution. Check out his book <a href=\"http://unconsciousbranding.com/\">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Day 3 Party: Dropbox </strong>With lots of competing parties, where to go/ Dropbox at <a href=\"http://shop.mellowjohnnys.com/?gclid=CIiAle7Wr8QCFQ8waQodon4ALw\">Mellow Johnny\'s Bike Shop</a>, of course! Great party, and a great 90\'s cover band, Angry Flannel (which founder Drew Houston is a member of). Nirvana, Jane\'s Addiction, represented!</p>\r\n<p><strong>Roundup - Day 4</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Panel: <em>Everything Eric Ries Has Learned Since 2011</em>, Eric Ries, Ted Greenwald</strong> Fans of <a href=\"http://theleanstartup.com/\">The Lean Startup</a> author, rejoice! Eric Ries announced a new book, crowd-sourced on Kickstarter, called <a href=\"http://www.fastcompany.com/3043745/most-creative-people/the-lean-startup-author-eric-ries-is-crowdsourcing-his-next-book-via-ki\">The Leader\'s Guide</a>. Don\'t be intimidated - just be entertained - by the number of special \'packages\' you can choose from - it\'s part of the gimmick! For reference, I went with the All-Access Package.</p>\r\n<p>Quick shout out to my new friends at Tech.co, Chute, Partnered, and General Assembly - great meeting you guys. Rock on, Austin, and see you in 2016!</p>','','','inherit','open','open','','254-revision-v1','','','2015-03-18 19:54:33','2015-03-18 19:54:33','',254,'http://abbot-water.com/254-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(256,1,'2015-03-18 19:54:51','2015-03-18 19:54:51','Hello from Austin and another SXSW!\r\n\r\nEvery year, the Interactive part of the festival grows bigger, and this year was no exception. If you\'ve never been, know this: it’s not a place for the faint of heart. This is a day-to-night affair, non-stop, for four days. It\'s panels, parties and pop-ups throughout the city, and it’s a great way to meet and connect with people you would never have met otherwise.\r\n\r\nBy request, I put together a roundup of what I think are the best of the best, by day, with commentary (below). Check out the content and the companies - it\'s worth your time. And if you do nothing else, do these three things: 1. Follow <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tnpuig\">Tomas Puig on Twitter</a>, who\'s workshop with Paul Dery was the single best thing I attended; 2. Buy Rick Webb\'s <a href=\"http://rickwebb.tumblr.com/\"><em>Agency: The Book</em></a><em>, </em>which sold out at SXSW; 3. Check out <a href=\"https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/881308232/only-on-kickstarter-the-leaders-guide-by-eric-ries\">Eric Ries\' crowd-sourced new book</a>, available only on Kickstarter and announced yesterday at SXSW.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 1</strong></p>\r\n<strong>Panel: <em>How to Remain Relevant in Today’s Digital Age, </em>Charles Barkley and Richard Deistch</strong> The conversation didn’t follow the panel title, but it was entertaining and filled with Barkley’s one-liners and a firm explanation of why he’s not on social media: it’s become a mean-spirited place. My favorite? His take on analytics: <em>Analytics is just stats. They just charge you more when they call it analytics. But it’s just stats.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Popup: How to Be a Change Agent, Brand Innovators </strong>An oasis in the SXSW storm, Brand Innovators hosted a full day of terrific programming and presentations featuring marketers, tech, and start-ups. If you are a brand marketer and don\'t attend their events, you should. <a href=\"http://brand-innovators.com/events/\">Find their calendar here.</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Party: NYT Magazine Relaunch Party</strong> Nothing much about the Times or the Magazine, but it did feature a great band, <a href=\"http://www.thesuffers.com/\"><em>The Suffers</em></a><em>, </em>at a classic venue – Mohawk on Red River.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 2</strong></p>\r\n<strong>Workshop: <em>Adv. Brand Marketing for Early Stage Companies, </em>Paul Dury and Tomas Puig</strong> The single best thing at SXSW. Marketing dollars + activities at early-stage companies need a different approach, and this four-hour workshop featured great content, in a digestible presentation and discussion, led by two experts. From how VC\'s judge a start-up via LTV and CAC to the basics of identifying your target market and USP, and addressing org structure of the modern marketing department, the material here was spot-on. And, contrast of Tomas and Paul\'s backgrounds brought the material to life in a relevant way. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tnpuig\">Tweet them for slides</a>!\r\n\r\n<strong>Day 2 Party: Rick Webb at the Yieldbot House </strong>Thanks to Yieldbot and Rick Webb for BBQ, Music, and FUN. The party celebrated <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Agency-Starting-Creative-Marketing-Advertising/dp/1137279869\">Rick\'s new book</a>, which is terrific. You can also catch my favorite post of his on Medium <a href=\"https://medium.com/galleys/f-king-timesheets-b3bb9d64beb8\">here</a>.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 3</strong></p>\r\n<strong>Day 3 Panel: <em>Future 15s Humans Not Consumers: Unconscious Emotions and Actions</em>, Douglas Van Praet </strong>A fascinating discussion about how we make choices - consciously and unconsciously - driven by emotion. The \"I like it and I don\'t know why\" effect is powerful, and Van Praet makes a good case for marketers to consider \'pattern interruption\' in creative execution. Check out his book <a href=\"http://unconsciousbranding.com/\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Day 3 Party: Dropbox </strong>With lots of competing parties, where to go/ Dropbox at <a href=\"http://shop.mellowjohnnys.com/?gclid=CIiAle7Wr8QCFQ8waQodon4ALw\">Mellow Johnny\'s Bike Shop</a>, of course! Great party, and a great 90\'s cover band, Angry Flannel (which founder Drew Houston is a member of). Nirvana, Jane\'s Addiction, represented!\r\n\r\n<strong>Roundup - Day 4</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Panel: <em>Everything Eric Ries Has Learned Since 2011</em>, Eric Ries, Ted Greenwald</strong> Fans of <a href=\"http://theleanstartup.com/\">The Lean Startup</a> author, rejoice! Eric Ries announced a new book, crowd-sourced on Kickstarter, called <a href=\"http://www.fastcompany.com/3043745/most-creative-people/the-lean-startup-author-eric-ries-is-crowdsourcing-his-next-book-via-ki\">The Leader\'s Guide</a>. Don\'t be intimidated - just be entertained - by the number of special \'packages\' you can choose from - it\'s part of the gimmick! For reference, I went with the All-Access Package.\r\n\r\nQuick shout out to my new friends at Tech.co, Chute, Partnered, and General Assembly - great meeting you guys. Rock on, Austin, and see you in 2016!','Hello from Austin and another SXSW!','','inherit','open','open','','254-revision-v1','','','2015-03-18 19:54:51','2015-03-18 19:54:51','',254,'http://abbot-water.com/254-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(257,1,'2015-03-18 19:55:12','2015-03-18 19:55:12','','SXSW LI','','inherit','open','open','','sxsw-li','','','2015-03-18 19:55:12','2015-03-18 19:55:12','',254,'http://abbot-water.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/SXSW-LI.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),
